{"id":8185,"date":"2019-11-12T06:13:21","date_gmt":"2019-11-12T12:13:21","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/new_logo_and_cover_for_the_atlantic_done_in_house.php"},"modified":"2019-11-12T06:13:21","modified_gmt":"2019-11-12T12:13:21","slug":"new_logo_and_cover_for_the_atlantic_done_in_house","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/new_logo_and_cover_for_the_atlantic_done_in_house.php","title":{"rendered":"New Logo and Cover for <em>The Atlantic<\/em> done In-house"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>(Est. 1857) &#8220;<a href=\"https:\/\/www.theatlantic.com\/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>The Atlantic<\/em><\/a> is an American magazine and multi-platform publisher. It was founded in 1857 in Boston, Massachusetts, as <em>The Atlantic Monthly<\/em>, a literary and cultural commentary magazine. After experiencing financial hardship and undergoing several ownership changes in the late 20th century, the magazine was purchased by businessman David G. Bradley, who refashioned it as a general editorial magazine primarily aimed at a target audience of serious national readers and &#8220;thought leaders&#8221;. In 2010, The Atlantic posted its first profit in a decade. In 2016 the periodical was named Magazine of the Year by the American Society of Magazine Editors. In July 2017, Bradley sold a majority interest in the publication to Laurene Powell Jobs&#8217;s Emerson Collective. Its website, TheAtlantic.com, provides daily coverage and analysis of breaking news, politics and international affairs, education, technology, health, science, and culture.&#8221; (<a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Atlantic\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Wikipedia<\/a>)<\/p>\n<!--more--><figure class=\"full\">\n<img src=\"https:\/\/www.underconsideration.com\/brandnew\/archives\/the_atlantic_2019_logo_evolution.gif\" alt=\"New Logo and Cover for &lt;em&g